"""
MKT Original Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 29–31
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-2chronicles-29-31.py

Ch 29: Hezekiah cleanses and reconsecrates the temple. Key terms: hithqaddĕšû
       (consecrate yourselves, v5); hanniddâ (impurity/filth, v5); likrōt bĕrît
       (cut a covenant, v10); sĕmîkâ (hand-laying, v23); the synchronized beginning
       of sacrifice and praise (v27) as liturgical theology.

Ch 30: All-Israel Passover — the legitimate second-month provision (Num 9:10-11, v2-3);
       šûḇ (return, v6); qāšâ ʿōrep (stiff-necked, v8); the Sinai covenant formula
       ḥannûn wĕraḥûm (v9); Hezekiah's prayer for those eating in impurity (v18-19)
       — seeking-heart overrides ritual purity; the Solomon comparison (v26).

Ch 31: Administrative covenant faithfulness — tithe heaps; Azariah's blessing-abundance
       declaration (v10); triple virtue formula ṭôḇ/yāšār/ʾĕmet (v20); and the closing
       dāraš formula "seeking his God with all his heart" (v21) as the Chronicler's
       ultimate commendation of Hezekiah.

Key decisions:
- dāraš (seek) tracked as the theological keyword across all three chapters
- "Cut a covenant" preserved literally in v29:10 to keep the covenantal idiom
- Num 9:10-11 second-month Passover provision cited explicitly for ch 30:2-3
- The prayer in 30:18-19 treated as the theological centre of ch 30
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON2 = {
  "29": {
    "1": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s regnal formula: 25 years old at accession, reigning 29 years. The parallel account in 2 Kings 18:1-3 is nearly identical, but the Chronicler devotes three chapters to what Kings covers in a few verses. The disproportion reveals the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological priority: Hezekiah&rsquo;s temple reforms, all-Israel Passover, and administrative covenant faithfulness are the defining acts of his reign, more significant than the Assyrian crisis (2 Kgs 18-19, treated briefly in 2 Chr 32).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Davidic evaluation: he did right &ldquo;just as his ancestor David had done.&rdquo; The explicit Davidic comparison is reserved for the most commendable kings in Chronicles (cf. 2 Chr 17:3 — Jehoshaphat; 34:2 — Josiah). This is the highest possible verdict the Chronicler can render. The phrase &ldquo;his ancestor David&rdquo; (<em>Dāwid ʾāḇîw</em>) — literally &ldquo;David his father&rdquo; — uses the Hebrew idiom of ancestor-as-father that underlines dynastic continuity.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;In the first year of his reign, in the first month.&rdquo; Hezekiah begins his reform at the earliest possible moment — month one, year one. The temporal precision is theologically significant in Chronicles: prompt obedience is a mark of covenant integrity (cf. 2 Chr 14:3 — Asa begins reforms immediately; 17:7 — Jehoshaphat acts in his third year). The opening of the temple doors is not merely administrative — it is the symbolic reversal of Ahaz&rsquo;s apostasy (2 Chr 28:24: Ahaz shut the doors).</p>",
    "4": "<p>He assembles priests and Levites in the open square on the east side — the public gathering space east of the temple before the Nicanor Gate. The assembly is formal and public: the king summons the religious establishment to hear a royal-prophetic address, the pattern of covenant renewal throughout Chronicles (cf. 2 Chr 15:9-10; 23:1-3; 34:29-30).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Hezekiah&rsquo;s address begins with the double command: <em>hithqaddĕšû</em> (consecrate yourselves — reflexive hitpael of <em>qādaš</em>: subject and object are the same person) and <em>qaddĕšû</em> (consecrate the house — piel active). The internal purification (self-consecration) must precede the external purification (temple cleansing). The word <em>hanniddâ</em> (the filth/impurity — the same root as <em>niddâ</em>, menstrual impurity) is applied to the temple: the most intimate language of uncleanness is applied to YHWH&rsquo;s house under Ahaz, marking the depth of desecration.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Hezekiah identifies with the fathers&rsquo; unfaithfulness: &ldquo;our fathers were unfaithful (<em>māʿalû</em>).&rdquo; The verb <em>māʿal</em> (act faithlessly/commit a breach of trust against) is a covenant-violation term that occurs frequently in Chronicles as the diagnostic of apostasy (cf. 1 Chr 2:7; 2 Chr 26:16, 18; 28:19, 22; 36:14). &ldquo;Turned their backs (<em>ʿōrep</em>) on him&rdquo; — literally &ldquo;gave the back of the neck&rdquo; — is the body-language idiom for complete rejection and contempt (Jer 2:27; 32:33).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The three cult crimes under Ahaz are named: doors shut, lamps extinguished, incense and burnt offerings stopped. Each item corresponds to a specific element of the Mosaic cultus: the doors controlled access to the divine presence; the lampstand (Exod 27:20-21) represented the perpetual light before YHWH; the morning and evening burnt offerings (Exod 29:38-42) and incense (Exod 30:7-8) were the two pillars of daily temple service. To shut and extinguish them all is the systematic dismantling of the Mosaic covenant order.</p>",
    "8": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s wrath (<em>qeṣep</em>) has made Judah and Jerusalem an object of &ldquo;horror, terror, and mockery&rdquo; (<em>zĕwāʿâ lĕšammâ wĕliššĕrēqâ</em>). This triad is Jeremianic language (Jer 18:16; 25:9, 11, 18; 29:18; Lam 2:15-16) that the Chronicler applies to the Ahaz era rather than the Babylonian exile — recognizing that the covenant curses were already operative in Judah before the final deportation. The audience knows the triad from prophetic tradition; Hezekiah is saying: what Jeremiah warned about, Ahaz already provoked.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Our sons and daughters and wives are in captivity because of this.&rdquo; The reference is to the Philistine and Edomite raids and the Israelite captives taken in Pekah&rsquo;s invasion (2 Chr 28:5-8, 17-18). The effect of apostasy is not abstract punishment but concrete family dissolution — the most intimate sphere of covenant community (wives, sons, daughters) disrupted. This personalizes the covenant argument: unfaithfulness is not a priestly abstraction but devastates households.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;I intend to make (<em>likrōt</em>) a covenant with the LORD.&rdquo; The phrase <em>kārat bĕrît</em> — literally &ldquo;cut a covenant&rdquo; — is the standard covenant-making idiom (cf. Gen 15:18; Exod 24:8; Jer 31:31). The idiom likely derives from the ancient practice of cutting animals in covenant rituals (Gen 15:9-17). MKT preserves &ldquo;make a covenant&rdquo; (standard idiom) rather than a literal translation. Hezekiah frames the entire temple reform as a covenant act: not merely institutional maintenance but relational restoration.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;Do not be negligent (<em>ʾal tiššāʾû</em>).&rdquo; The verb <em>šāʿâ</em> (be negligent/slack/careless) is rare; it refers to the inattentive or indifferent posture that leads to neglect of duty. The motivation: &ldquo;the LORD has chosen (<em>bāḥar</em>) you to stand before him, to minister to him and to burn incense to him.&rdquo; Election creates obligation — the Levites have been chosen for a specific vocation, and negligence would be a betrayal of divine calling (cf. Num 16:9 — the Levites&rsquo; election to stand before the congregation).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Levitical response: fourteen named leaders rise from four Kohathite families (Mahath-Amasai, Joel-Azariah, Kish-Abdi, Azariah-Jehaleleel) and two Merarite ones (Joah-Zimmah, Eden-Joah) followed by Gershonites, Elizaphanites, and the three musical families (Asaph, Heman, Jeduthun — vv13-14). The full Levitical establishment is mobilized; the listing of all fourteen by name underlines the completeness and formality of the response to the royal-covenantal call.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Shimri and Jeiel from Elizaphan&rsquo;s sons; Zechariah and Mattaniah from Asaph&rsquo;s sons. The Asaphite Zechariah and Mattaniah are not the same individuals as in 1 Chr 25 but represent the continuing line of the temple musical guild. The Chronicler traces the institutional continuity of Levitical service across generations through these named lists — the named individuals make the continuity concrete rather than merely abstract.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jehiel and Shimei from Heman&rsquo;s sons; Shemaiah and Uzziel from Jeduthun&rsquo;s sons. All three of the great musical families named in 1 Chr 25 are represented in Hezekiah&rsquo;s renewal. The Chronicler establishes that Davidic temple music is not lost or forgotten — its institutional carriers are present and ready when the king calls for renewal.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;They went in — as the king commanded, by the word of the LORD (<em>bidĕḇar YHWH</em>).&rdquo; This phrase, added to what might otherwise be a routine royal order, transforms the command&rsquo;s authority: the king commands and the Levites comply, but the Chronicler specifies that the royal word is aligned with the divine word. The same formula appears at 1 Chr 15:15 (carrying the ark &ldquo;as the LORD had commanded&rdquo;) — it is the authenticating mark of legitimate cult reform.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The priests entered the inner sanctuary (<em>lipnîmâ</em> — the innermost part); the Levites carried the unclean material out to the Kidron Brook. The spatial movement is theologically precise: defilement moves outward from the holy to the unholy, from the inner sanctuary through the court to the brook that drained away from the city. The Kidron Valley was the standard disposal site for cult pollutants (cf. 2 Chr 15:16 — Maacah&rsquo;s Asherah idol; 30:14 — incense altars).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The purification work: 16 days total — eight days to reach the vestibule, eight more days to complete the house. The work completes on the sixteenth day of the first month — two days after the fourteenth (Passover day). This explains why ch 30 celebrates Passover in the second month: the temple was ready only on the 16th, so a month-one Passover was technically impossible. The Chronicler presents the timing as providential: the temple&rsquo;s unavailability triggers the use of the legitimate second-month provision (Num 9:10-11).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The Levites report to Hezekiah: the full scope of purification is described — &ldquo;the entire house of the LORD, including the altar of burnt offering with all its vessels and the table of the showbread with all its vessels.&rdquo; The double &ldquo;with all its vessels&rdquo; underlines thoroughness: not just the structural elements but every associated piece of equipment is reconsecrated. The altar and the table are the two central pieces of the daily service (Exod 30:1-10; 25:23-30).</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;All the vessels that King Ahaz set aside during his unfaithful reign we have prepared and consecrated.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;set aside&rdquo; (<em>hizānāḥ</em> — pushed aside/rejected/cast away) is a strong verb of deliberate rejection (cf. Ps 44:9, 23; 60:1, 10; Hos 8:3). Ahaz did not simply neglect the vessels — he actively repudiated them. Their reconsecration reverses a deliberate act of apostasy, not merely a period of neglect.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Hezekiah rose early (<em>wayyaškem Ḥizqiyyāhû</em>) and gathered the city&rsquo;s officials.&rdquo; The idiom <em>šākem</em> (rise early/act promptly — literally &ldquo;shoulder an early burden&rdquo;) signals urgency and devotion: the king treats the restoration of worship as a priority that cannot wait. The same idiom is used of Abraham rising early to obey the command about Isaac (Gen 22:3) and of the prophets YHWH repeatedly sent &ldquo;rising early to send them&rdquo; (Jer 7:25; 25:4).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The sin offering: seven bulls, seven rams, seven lambs, and seven male goats. The number seven pervades sacred Israel&rsquo;s cultic numerology — seven is the covenant-completion number (cf. Gen 21:28-30; Num 23:1; Job 42:8). The fourfold seven (28 animals total) is a maximum sin offering. The recipients: &ldquo;for the kingdom, for the sanctuary, and for Judah&rdquo; — three domains that define the full scope of what has been defiled.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The sequential sacrificing and blood-sprinkling of bulls, rams, and lambs. The verb <em>zāraQ</em> (sprinkle/throw with force) is used for the priestly blood-manipulation in the burnt offering (not <em>nāzâ</em>, the smaller sprinkle of the sin offering). The blood is thrown (<em>zerîqâ</em>) against the altar in a wide arc covering the altar surface — the purification of the sanctuary&rsquo;s central object begins with this act.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;The male goats for the sin offering were brought before the king and the assembly, who laid their hands (<em>wayyismĕkû yĕdêhem</em>) on them.&rdquo; The hand-laying (<em>sĕmîkâ</em>) is the ritual act of identification — the worshipper transfers his guilt to the animal (Lev 1:4; 4:4, 15, 24, 29; 16:21). By involving the king and the whole assembly in the <em>sĕmîkâ</em>, Hezekiah makes the atonement communal and representative — a whole-people act of covenant renewal.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;The priests slaughtered them and made a sin offering with their blood on the altar to atone for all Israel.&rdquo; The phrase <em>lĕkappēr ʿal kol Yiśrāʾēl</em> (to atone for all Israel) is the most far-reaching atonement statement in Chronicles. Hezekiah&rsquo;s offering explicitly covers the northern tribes — not just Judah or Jerusalem. The verb <em>kāpar</em> (cover/atone — the root of Kippur/Day of Atonement) is used here of a historical king&rsquo;s unprecedented intercession on behalf of the divided nation.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;He stationed the Levites with instruments as commanded by David, by Gad the king&rsquo;s seer, and by Nathan the prophet — for the commandment was from the LORD through his prophets.&rdquo; The triple prophetic authority (David + Gad + Nathan) establishes the highest possible warrant for the Levitical music: it is not Davidic innovation but divine command mediated through three recognized prophets. MKT renders &ldquo;the king&rsquo;s seer&rdquo; (<em>ḥōzeh hammelek</em>) as distinct from &ldquo;the prophet&rdquo; (<em>nāḇîʾ</em>) — preserving the original two-title distinction.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The Levites with David&rsquo;s instruments; the priests with the trumpets. The two instrument groups are assigned to their respective personnel: Levitical harps, lyres, and cymbals (the instruments of prophetic praise, 1 Chr 25:1) for the Levites; the <em>ḥăṣōṣĕrôt</em> (silver trumpets) prescribed for the Aaronic priests (Num 10:1-10). The liturgical arrangement preserves the distinctions of Mosaic law even within a unified act of worship.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;At the moment the burnt offering began, the song to the LORD also began.&rdquo; The synchronization of sacrifice and praise is theologically profound: the physical act (animal sacrifice on the altar) and the audible act (praise with instruments and voice) begin simultaneously. Neither precedes the other. The Chronicler presents sacrifice and praise as a single integrated offering — two inseparable dimensions of approaching God. MKT renders the temporal particle <em>bĕʿēt heḥēl</em> (at the time/moment of the beginning) to preserve the simultaneity.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;The whole congregation bowed in worship while the singers sang and the trumpeters sounded, continuing until the burnt offering was complete.&rdquo; The duration of the congregational prostration precisely matches the duration of the sacrifice — the posture of worship is sustained for the entire act. The three verbs — bowed (<em>hištaḥăwû</em>), sang (<em>mĕšōrĕrîm mĕšōrĕrîm</em>), sounded (<em>ḥōṣĕrîm mĕḥaṣĕrîm</em>) — are all active participles, emphasizing continuous action rather than a single moment.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;When the offering was finished, the king and everyone with him bowed and worshipped.&rdquo; The king&rsquo;s prostration at the completion of the sacrifice is the public embodiment of covenant submission. Hezekiah does not stand as a spectator or a sponsor but participates in the full liturgical act. The king who commanded the reform also performs the required act of worship — his authority is not exemption from but expression of the covenant obligation.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Hezekiah commands the Levites to sing &ldquo;in the words of David and of Asaph the seer (<em>ḥōzeh</em>).&rdquo; The Psalms of David and Asaph are named as the authorized liturgical text — the Chronicler frames the Psalter as the official scripture of temple praise. Asaph is called <em>ḥōzeh</em> (seer) — a prophetic title — confirming that the psalms are not merely poetry but inspired vision. They sang &ldquo;with joy (<em>bĕśimḥâ</em>)&rdquo; and then &ldquo;bowed and worshipped (<em>hiqqĕdû wayyištaḥăwû</em>)&rdquo; — the alternation of praise-song and prostration as the two basic postures of biblical worship.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;Now that you have consecrated yourselves (<em>millĕʾtem yĕdkem laYHWH</em> — literally &lsquo;filled your hands for the LORD&rsquo;)&rdquo; — the idiom <em>millēʾ yādayim</em> (fill the hand) is the technical term for priestly ordination (Exod 29:29; Lev 8:33; 1 Kgs 13:33). Hezekiah is inviting the whole congregation to participate in what is technically priestly action — a democratization of the ordination idiom. The &ldquo;thank offerings&rdquo; (<em>tôdôt</em> — the <em>tôdâ</em> offering, a peace offering accompanied by songs of praise) are the voluntary, gratitude-driven culmination of the worship sequence.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The numbers of the congregational burnt offering: 70 bulls, 100 rams, 200 lambs — 370 animals total. These are round numbers in characteristic patterns (cf. 2 Chr 30:24: 1,000 + 7,000; 1,000 + 10,000). The scale of voluntary offering indicates the depth of the congregation&rsquo;s response to the renewal — not merely formal compliance but enthusiastic participation.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The consecrated offerings (beyond the burnt offerings): 600 oxen and 3,000 sheep. These &ldquo;consecrated offerings&rdquo; (<em>qŏdāšîm</em>) are the fellowship/peace offerings whose meat is shared among offerer, priest, and community. The enormous scale means an extended feast — the whole congregation eating and celebrating together. The communal meal that follows sacrifice is the culminating act of covenant restoration.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&ldquo;There were not enough priests to skin all the burnt offerings, so their Levite brothers helped them.&rdquo; The practical logistical detail reveals a subtle critique: the Levites &ldquo;were more conscientious in consecrating themselves (<em>kî haLĕwiyyîm yĕšārîm lēḇāḇ lĕhitqaddēš</em>) than the priests.&rdquo; Literally &ldquo;the Levites were more upright of heart to consecrate themselves&rdquo; — the Chronicler commends Levitical zeal at the expense of priestly tardiness. This is one of several Chronicles passages that elevates the Levitical role relative to the Aaronic (cf. 1 Chr 15:2, 11-13; 2 Chr 30:3).</p>",
    "35": "<p>The burnt offerings, fellowship-offering fat, and drink offerings were all &ldquo;plentiful&rdquo; (<em>lĕrōḇ</em>) — the temple service was restored to its full order. The phrase &ldquo;so the service of the LORD&rsquo;s house was restored to order&rdquo; (<em>wattikkôn ʿăḇōdat bêt YHWH</em>) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s summary verdict on the entire purification project. <em>Kûn</em> (be established/set in order/prepared) is the word for the proper arrangement of the sanctuary — what Ahaz had disordered, Hezekiah has re-ordered.</p>",
    "36": "<p>&ldquo;Hezekiah and all the people rejoiced over what God had prepared for the people, for it had all happened so quickly.&rdquo; The explanation for the joy is theological: not Hezekiah&rsquo;s skill or the people&rsquo;s effort but what &ldquo;God had prepared (<em>hēkîn</em>) for the people.&rdquo; The same verb <em>kûn</em> (prepare/establish) used in v35 for the restored service is now attributed to God as its ultimate cause — God prepared the hearts, the workers, and the circumstances that made the rapid restoration possible. The rapidity itself is a sign of divine blessing.</p>"
  },
  "30": {
    "1": "<p>Hezekiah sends invitations throughout all Israel and Judah, including letters to Ephraim and Manasseh. Writing to the northern tribes — by this point largely under Assyrian occupation after Tiglath-pileser III&rsquo;s campaigns (734-732 BCE) and Sargon II&rsquo;s final deportation (722 BCE) — is unprecedented. The Chronicler presents Hezekiah as the king who refuses to accept the political division of Israel as the final word on the covenant community&rsquo;s unity.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The second-month Passover is grounded in Num 9:10-11: those who are unclean or on a journey may observe Passover in the second month on the fourteenth day. Hezekiah invokes this legitimate provision because of two specific impediments: insufficient priestly consecration and the people not yet assembled (v3). The Chronicler demonstrates that Hezekiah&rsquo;s accommodation is not arbitrary creativity but careful application of Torah provision.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The two stated reasons for the delay — insufficient priestly consecration and people not assembled — are both temporary, curable conditions. The implication is that the remedy was underway: priests were consecrating themselves (ch 29:34 notes their eventual sufficiency) and the assembly was being gathered. MKT renders &ldquo;not enough priests had consecrated themselves&rdquo; rather than a stronger reading, to preserve the factual rather than fault-ascribing tone of the verse.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The plan &ldquo;seemed right&rdquo; (<em>wayyiššar haddāḇār</em>) to the king and the assembly — the idiom of legitimate corporate decision-making (cf. 1 Chr 13:2; Acts 15:28: &ldquo;it seemed right to the Holy Spirit and to us&rdquo;). The decision is not unilateral royal decree but consensus of king and assembly, mirroring the covenant-renewal assemblies throughout Chronicles.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The decree goes out &ldquo;from Beersheba to Dan&rdquo; — the traditional formulation for all Israel from south to north (cf. Judg 20:1; 1 Sam 3:20; 2 Sam 3:10). The breadth of the invitation is the key point: this Passover is not a regional Jerusalem celebration but a summons to the whole covenant people regardless of the political border that now separates Israel from Judah. &ldquo;For it had not been celebrated in great numbers as prescribed&rdquo; — acknowledging a long period of covenant neglect.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The letter&rsquo;s opening: &ldquo;People of Israel, return (<em>šûḇû</em>) to the LORD, the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Israel.&rdquo; The call to return (<em>šûḇ</em> — the covenant-return verb) invokes the patriarchal God by his full triple name — the name that encompasses the whole Abrahamic promise. The use of &ldquo;Israel&rdquo; (Jacob&rsquo;s covenant name) rather than &ldquo;Jacob&rdquo; as the third patriarch is deliberate: the northern tribes share a claim on the patriarch Israel and are being called back to that identity.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;Do not be like your fathers and brothers, who were unfaithful (<em>māʿalû</em>).&rdquo; The letter uses <em>māʿal</em> (covenant faithlessness) — the same verb Hezekiah used of his own fathers in 29:6. The identification of the northern tribes&rsquo; sin with Judah&rsquo;s own history of apostasy is irenic: Hezekiah does not condemn Israel as uniquely apostate but places them in a shared history of failure that includes Judah. The result — &ldquo;he made them a horror (<em>lĕšammâ</em>)&rdquo; — recycles the 29:8 language.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;Do not be stiff-necked (<em>qĕšê ʿōrep</em>) like your ancestors.&rdquo; The idiom <em>qāšâ ʿōrep</em> (hard of neck) is the Deuteronomic term for covenant resistance (Exod 32:9; 33:3, 5; Deut 9:6, 13; 10:16). The neck metaphor: an animal that refuses to yield to the yoke is &ldquo;stiff-necked.&rdquo; The appeal: &ldquo;submit to the LORD (<em>tĕnû yād laYHWH</em>) — literally &lsquo;give a hand to the LORD&rsquo; — the gesture of submission and covenant entry (cf. Lam 5:6). &ldquo;Come to his sanctuary which he has consecrated forever (<em>lĕʿôlām</em>)&rdquo; — the sanctuary&rsquo;s permanent divine dedication makes it always available for returning worshippers.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;For if you return (<em>tāšûḇû</em>) to the LORD, your brothers and children will find compassion (<em>rāḥămîm</em>) from their captors.&rdquo; The covenant motivation for return is practical: the exiled northern Israelites may be released if the remnant returns to YHWH. The ground: &ldquo;The LORD your God is gracious and merciful (<em>ḥannûn wĕraḥûm</em>).&rdquo; This is the Sinai covenant-name formula (Exod 34:6: <em>ḥannûn wĕraḥûm ʾerek ʾappayim wĕrab ḥesed wĕʾĕmet</em>), which grounds every prophetic call to return in the character of the God being addressed.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The couriers go through Ephraim, Manasseh, and Zebulun — &ldquo;but the people laughed and mocked them (<em>wayyiśḥăqû wĕyĕlallĕgû</em> ʿălêhem).&rdquo; The verb <em>śāḥaq</em> (laugh/mock) is the word for Sarah&rsquo;s disbelieving laughter at the promise (Gen 18:12-13) and for Ishmael&rsquo;s mocking of Isaac (Gen 21:9). The double verb (<em>śāḥaq</em> + <em>lāʿag</em>) indicates contemptuous derision — the invitation to covenant restoration is met with ridicule. This is the expected response from those whose apostasy is entrenched.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;Nevertheless, some men from Asher, Manasseh, and Zebulun humbled themselves (<em>kānĕʿû</em>) and came to Jerusalem.&rdquo; The remnant who respond are specifically those who &ldquo;humbled themselves&rdquo; — <em>kānaʿ</em> (humble/submit/be brought low) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s signature verb for the repentance that averts divine judgment (cf. 2 Chr 7:14; 12:6-7; 33:12, 19, 23). The specific tribes — Asher, Manasseh, Zebulun — all from the north and west — show the response was geographically distributed, not concentrated.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;In Judah too God&rsquo;s hand gave them one heart (<em>yad hāʾĕlōhîm hāytâ bihûdâ lātēt lāhem lēḇ ʾeḥād</em>).&rdquo; The divine sovereign gift of unified hearts is the precondition for covenant assembly. The phrase <em>lēḇ ʾeḥād</em> (one heart) appears in 1 Chr 12:38 for the all-Israel gathering at Hebron to make David king. Heart-unity is the gift of God, not the achievement of royal diplomacy — the same theology of Ezek 11:19; 36:26 (&ldquo;I will give them one heart&rdquo;).</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;A large crowd — a very great assembly (<em>qāhāl rāb mĕʾōd</em>).&rdquo; The characterization &ldquo;very great assembly&rdquo; is the maximum superlative of communal gathering in Chronicles — the same language used for Solomon&rsquo;s dedication assembly (1 Kgs 8:65) and the eschatological assembly of Rev 7:9. The Festival of Unleavened Bread in the second month marks the occasion: the seven-day feast that follows Passover extends the celebration and the communal gathering.</p>",
    "14": "<p>They remove the foreign altars and incense altars from Jerusalem and throw them into the Kidron Brook. The spontaneous cult-reform by the gathered assembly — not commanded by Hezekiah — indicates that genuine repentance is occurring: the people themselves act to purify the city before the feast. The Kidron Brook continues to be the disposal channel for cult contaminants (cf. 2 Chr 15:16; 29:16).</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;The priests and Levites were ashamed (<em>wayyēḇōšû</em>).&rdquo; The shame of the priests is a striking detail: they had not adequately consecrated themselves, but the sight of the people&rsquo;s spontaneous reform shamed them into action. The verb <em>bôš</em> (be ashamed/put to shame) is elsewhere used for the shame of those whose trust was misplaced (Ps 25:3; 31:1, 17; Isa 49:23). Here it is productive shame — the kind that motivates right action rather than paralysis.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The Levites receive the Passover blood and hand it to the priests, who sprinkle it — &ldquo;as prescribed, following the law of Moses the man of God.&rdquo; The explicit appeal to Mosaic law underlines Hezekiah&rsquo;s reform&rsquo;s legitimacy. &ldquo;Moses the man of God&rdquo; (<em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) is Moses&rsquo;s most honorific title in the Chronicler&rsquo;s vocabulary (cf. 1 Chr 23:14; Ezra 3:2; Neh 12:24) — invoking this title at the moment of describing Torah compliance signals maximum covenantal gravity.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Levites take over the slaughtering for those not ritually clean — a practical accommodation driven by the extraordinary circumstances. Numbers 9:10-11 authorized the second-month Passover for those ritually impure; the Levites extend the accommodation further by serving as proxy slaughterers for those who cannot themselves fulfil the requirement. The Chronicler presents this as legitimate expansion of Mosaic accommodation rather than violation — necessity and divine provision rather than disregard of the law.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;A large number of the people... had not purified themselves, yet they ate the Passover contrary to what was written.&rdquo; The Chronicler does not soften the admission: the second-month Passover was eaten by many who were still ritually impure — an objective violation of Lev 7:20-21. The solution is not ritual but intercessory: &ldquo;But Hezekiah prayed for them: &lsquo;May the good LORD pardon (<em>yĕkappēr</em>) everyone.&rsquo;&rdquo; The verb <em>kāpar</em> (atone/cover) appears — Hezekiah offers an intercessory prayer of atonement for those whose heart is right but whose ritual status is wrong.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;Who has set his heart to seek God (<em>lā&#x200B;dĕrōš lēʾlōhîm</em>), the LORD, the God of his ancestors, even if he is not cleansed as the sanctuary requires.&rdquo; This is the theological centrepiece of the chapter — and possibly of all Chronicles&rsquo; teaching on worship. Hezekiah&rsquo;s prayer establishes a priority: seeking-heart (<em>dāraš</em>) trumps ritual cleanness. The intention is decisive, not the technical status. This does not abolish the ritual requirements but establishes that God responds to sincere seeking even when full compliance is temporarily impossible — a principle with direct New Testament resonance (John 4:23-24).</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD listened to Hezekiah and healed (<em>wayyirpāʾ</em>) the people.&rdquo; The verb <em>rāpāʾ</em> (heal) is unexpected — the people were ritually impure, not physically sick. But the Chronicler uses healing language for YHWH&rsquo;s response to Hezekiah&rsquo;s intercession, treating ritual impurity as a kind of &ldquo;sickness&rdquo; of the community that divine mercy can address. The divine response is direct, immediate, and total — he &ldquo;healed&rdquo; them, removing the impurity&rsquo;s consequence through intercessory prayer.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Seven days of the Festival of Unleavened Bread with &ldquo;great joy&rdquo; (<em>śimḥâ gĕdôlâ</em>). &ldquo;The Levites and priests praised the LORD every day with resounding instruments.&rdquo; The word &ldquo;resounding&rdquo; (<em>kĕlê ʿōz laYHWH</em> — &ldquo;instruments of strength/force for the LORD&rdquo;) captures the intensity and power of the praise. Seven days of continuous daily praise — the same seven-day structure as the Feast of Booths (Lev 23:36) and Solomon&rsquo;s dedication feast (2 Chr 7:8-9).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Hezekiah &ldquo;spoke encouragingly (<em>wĕdibber ʿal lēḇ</em>) to all the Levites who showed skill and understanding in the LORD&rsquo;s service.&rdquo; The idiom <em>dibbēr ʿal lēḇ</em> — &ldquo;speak to the heart&rdquo; — is the language of intimate, reassuring address: Boaz to Ruth (Ruth 2:13), Joseph to his brothers (Gen 50:21), YHWH to Jerusalem (Isa 40:2). Hezekiah&rsquo;s personal encouragement of the Levites reflects the king&rsquo;s role as patron and sustainer of Levitical worship.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;Then the whole assembly decided to celebrate for another seven days, and they did so with great joy.&rdquo; The spontaneous extension of the feast for a second week is the congregation&rsquo;s own initiative — not a royal decree. The Chronicler underlines this: &ldquo;the whole assembly decided (<em>wayyiwwāʿăṣû</em>)&rdquo; — they took counsel and resolved. The assembly acts with covenantal agency, not merely royal compliance. The total fourteen-day feast matches Solomon&rsquo;s dedication feast (2 Chr 7:8-9: seven days + seven days = fourteen days).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The royal and official contributions: Hezekiah gives 1,000 bulls and 7,000 sheep; officials give 1,000 bulls and 10,000 sheep. The scale of royal generosity triggers priestly consecration: &ldquo;a great number of priests consecrated themselves.&rdquo; The connection is explicit — the abundance of sacrificial material creates the occasion and perhaps the incentive for delayed priestly consecrations. Covenant renewal creates its own momentum.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The composition of the full assembly is described: all Judah, the priests, the Levites, those who came from Israel, the &ldquo;foreigners (<em>gērîm</em>) who had come from Israel,&rdquo; and those who lived in Judah. The inclusion of <em>gērîm</em> (resident aliens) who came from northern Israel is significant — non-ethnic Israelites are full participants in the Passover, consistent with the Mosaic provision (Num 9:14; Exod 12:48-49).</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;There was great joy in Jerusalem — nothing like it had been seen since the time of Solomon son of David king of Israel.&rdquo; The explicit Solomon comparison is the Chronicler&rsquo;s highest possible praise for a post-Solomonic assembly. Solomon&rsquo;s dedication feast (2 Chr 7:8-10) is the benchmark; Hezekiah&rsquo;s Passover matches it in scale and joy. The phrase &ldquo;son of David king of Israel&rdquo; — not &ldquo;king of Judah&rdquo; — reminds the reader that Solomon was king of all Israel, and Hezekiah&rsquo;s all-Israel Passover is reaching for that same unity.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&ldquo;The priests and Levites stood up to bless the people (<em>lĕḇārēk</em>). Their voice was heard, and their prayer ascended (<em>wayyāḇōʾ</em>) to his holy dwelling place — to heaven (<em>lĕmāʿôn qodĕšô laššāmāyim</em>).&rdquo; The climactic verse of the chapter: the priestly blessing (Num 6:24-26) followed by the ascent of the prayer to the heavenly sanctuary. The phrase <em>mĕʿôn qodĕš</em> (holy habitation) is used of the heavenly temple in Ps 68:5; Deut 26:15; Isa 63:15 — YHWH&rsquo;s true dwelling is not the Jerusalem temple but heaven itself, of which the temple is the earthly counterpart.</p>"
  },
  "31": {
    "1": "<p>The comprehensive cult destruction that follows the feast: the Israelites present break sacred pillars, cut down Asherah poles, demolish high places and altars throughout Judah, Benjamin, Ephraim, and Manasseh. The geographical scope — including the former northern kingdom territories — is the physical implementation of the Passover&rsquo;s all-Israel vision. The feast generated the communal will; the people execute the reform themselves on their way home.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Hezekiah reorganizes the priestly and Levitical divisions according to their assignments. The phrase &ldquo;each in his specific service&rdquo; (<em>kĕpî maḥălĕqōtām</em>) echoes the organizational language of 1 Chr 23-26 — Hezekiah is restoring the Davidic temple organization that had presumably fallen into disarray under Ahaz. The specific roles: burnt offerings, peace offerings, ministering, giving thanks, and praise — each with assigned personnel.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The king contributes from his own possessions for the daily (morning and evening) burnt offerings and those for Sabbaths, new moons, and appointed feasts, &ldquo;as prescribed in the law of the LORD (<em>kĕkātûḇ bĕtôrat YHWH</em>).&rdquo; The formula &ldquo;as written in the law of the LORD&rdquo; is the formal citation formula for Mosaic instruction (cf. 2 Chr 23:18; 30:16; 35:12; Neh 8:14). The king&rsquo;s personal funding of the regular public sacrifices is a royal obligation that Hezekiah voluntarily accepts.</p>",
    "4": "<p>He commands the people of Jerusalem to give the portion due to priests and Levites &ldquo;so that they could devote themselves fully to the law of the LORD (<em>yĕḥazĕqû bĕtôrat YHWH</em>).&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;devote themselves fully&rdquo; — literally &ldquo;be strong in the Torah of the LORD&rdquo; (<em>ḥāzaq bĕ</em>-) — uses the commissioning verb <em>ḥāzaq</em> in a new application: not courage in battle but strength in Torah study and teaching. The connection between tithe-giving and Torah-devotion is explicit: financial support of the clergy enables full-time covenant instruction.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;As soon as the order spread, the Israelites brought in abundance the firstfruits of grain, wine, oil, honey, and all the produce of the field, and they brought in the tithe of everything in abundance.&rdquo; The double &ldquo;in abundance&rdquo; (<em>lĕrōḇ</em>) signals the overflow-blessing that covenant faithfulness produces (cf. Mal 3:10: &ldquo;test me in this... and see if I will not open the floodgates of heaven and pour out so much blessing&rdquo;). The tithe is the covenant&rsquo;s built-in test of trust: give to YHWH and receive back in overflow.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The people of Israel and Judah brought the tithe of cattle and sheep and of dedicated things (<em>qŏdāšîm</em>). The joint mention of &ldquo;Israel and Judah&rdquo; bringing tithes together confirms that the all-Israel Passover vision has material consequence: northern remnants are now contributing to the Jerusalem temple treasury alongside Judah. The dedicated things being tithed reflect additional levels of covenant commitment beyond the basic tithe obligations.</p>",
    "7": "<p>They began piling up the heaps in the third month (Sivan — the month of Pentecost/Shavuot, harvest festival) and finished in the seventh month (Tishri — the month of Tabernacles/Sukkot, final harvest). The accumulation covers exactly the main harvest period — four months of continuous abundance. The deliberate mention of the months frames the material blessing within the sacred calendar: covenant giving flows in rhythm with the appointed festivals.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Hezekiah and the officials see the heaps and &ldquo;blessed the LORD and his people Israel.&rdquo; The double blessing — of YHWH and of his people — mirrors the covenant blessing formula: to bless YHWH is to acknowledge his gifts; to bless Israel is to recognize them as the instrument of God&rsquo;s provision and the beneficiary of his faithfulness. The officials&rsquo; response is doxological rather than administrative: the first response to covenant abundance is worship.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Hezekiah questions the priests and Levites about the heaps — his inquiry is the administrative expression of responsible stewardship. The king who organizes and funds the temple service also verifies its proper management. The combination of generosity (v3) and accountability (v9) models the covenant king&rsquo;s double obligation: provide and verify.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Azariah the chief priest of the house of Zadok answers: &ldquo;Since the people began bringing offerings, we have had enough to eat, with plenty left over — for the LORD has blessed his people, and this great amount is what is left over.&rdquo; Azariah&rsquo;s testimony invokes the principle of Mal 3:10 and 2 Cor 9:8: &ldquo;God is able to make all grace overflow to you, so that... you will overflow in every good work.&rdquo; The surplus is the sign of YHWH&rsquo;s blessing — <em>mehaḇrēk YHWH ʾet ʿammô</em> (from the blessing of the LORD upon his people).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Hezekiah commands storage chambers (<em>lĕšākôt</em>) to be built in the temple complex for the surplus tithes. The word <em>liškat</em> (chamber/room) is the same word used for the temple chambers in Nehemiah (Neh 10:38-39; 13:4-9), where Nehemiah has to reform abuses in their use. Hezekiah&rsquo;s creation of proper storage infrastructure is the administrative counterpart to the theological reform — orderly storage of God&rsquo;s gifts requires proper facilities.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Cononiah the Levite is in charge of contributions, tithes, and dedicated things, with his brother Shimei as assistant. The distribution system has a named Levitical administrator at its head — accountability is personal, not merely procedural. The emphasis on &ldquo;faithfully&rdquo; (<em>bĕʾĕmûnâ</em>) — trustworthily/faithfully — underlines that covenant stewardship requires personal integrity, not merely correct procedure.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Ten overseers under Cononiah are listed: Jehiel, Azaziah, Nahath, Asahel, Jerimoth, Jozabad, Eliel, Ismachiah, Mahath, and Benaiah — all &ldquo;by appointment of King Hezekiah and Azariah the chief of God&rsquo;s house.&rdquo; The dual authority — royal and priestly — for the administrative appointments reflects the governance structure of the Chronicler&rsquo;s ideal: civil and sacred authority working together rather than in competition.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Kore son of Imnah, keeper of the East Gate, handles freewill offerings and distribution of contributions &ldquo;reserved for the LORD.&rdquo; The East Gate was the primary entrance to the temple court — its keeper held a prominent and trust-requiring position. The freewill offerings (<em>nĕdābôt</em>) are particularly sensitive since they are voluntary above-and-beyond contributions; their fair distribution required someone of proven integrity.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Eden, Miniamin, Jeshua, Shemaiah, Amariah, and Shecaniah distribute portions in the priestly cities, &ldquo;faithfully distributing... great and small alike (<em>laggādôl kĕqāṭān</em>).&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;great and small alike&rdquo; echoes the principles of equal treatment in the law (Deut 1:17; 16:18-19) and the lot-casting for the musical divisions (1 Chr 25:8). The covenant community&rsquo;s resources are distributed without favoritism toward the prominent.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Besides those enrolled by genealogy, they distributed daily portions to every male from three years old and upward.&rdquo; The daily portion for temple-serving personnel and their dependents extends even to young children — three years as the minimum age for inclusion suggests the child has moved from nursing to basic food participation. The genealogical enrollment is the administrative mechanism that prevents fraudulent claims while ensuring no legitimate beneficiary is overlooked.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Priests enrolled by ancestral family; Levites from twenty years and upward in their assigned positions. The age threshold for Levitical service (twenty) reflects the Davidic adjustment of 1 Chr 23:24-27 — the temple&rsquo;s permanent status justified beginning service at twenty rather than thirty. Hezekiah&rsquo;s organization directly implements David&rsquo;s administrative provision.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The genealogical record includes &ldquo;all their little children, their wives, their sons and daughters — the entire assembly — for they faithfully consecrated themselves in holiness (<em>bĕʾĕmûnātām yitqaddĕšû bĕqōdeš</em>).&rdquo; The whole priestly and Levitical household is enrolled, not merely the active male servants. The reason — they faithfully consecrated themselves — grounds the inclusion in personal covenant integrity rather than merely genealogical entitlement.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The sons of Aaron in the common pasturelands of their cities have designated distributors appointed by name in every city. The logistical detail ensures that priests serving in their home cities (the 48 priestly and Levitical cities of Josh 21) receive their portions even when not serving in Jerusalem. The named distributors in every city extend the system to the full geographic breadth of the priestly establishment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The summary commendation: &ldquo;Hezekiah acted throughout all Judah, doing what was good and right and faithful (<em>haṭṭôḇ wĕhayyāšār wĕhāʾĕmet</em>) before the LORD his God.&rdquo; The triple virtue formula — <em>ṭôḇ</em> (good), <em>yāšār</em> (right/upright), <em>ʾĕmet</em> (faithful/true) — is the fullest commendation in the Chronicler&rsquo;s evaluative vocabulary (cf. Neh 9:13: the Torah is described with the same three qualities). MKT renders all three rather than conflating them.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;In every work he undertook in the service of the house of God, in the law, and in the commandments, seeking his God with all his heart (<em>ûḇĕkol lĕḇāḇô</em>) — he prospered (<em>wayyaṣlîaḥ</em>).&rdquo; The closing formula of Hezekiah&rsquo;s temple-reform narrative invokes the Deuteronomic promise directly (Deut 29:9; Josh 1:7-8: obey the Torah and &ldquo;you will be prosperous and successful&rdquo;). The verb <em>ṣālaḥ</em> (prosper/succeed) is the covenant blessing-word for those who seek YHWH wholeheartedly. The final word of the narrative is <em>wayyaṣlîaḥ</em> — he prospered — the Chronicler&rsquo;s seal on three chapters of covenant faithfulness.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-original', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, CHRON2)
    save_comm('mkt-original', '2chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in CHRON2.values())
    print(f'2chronicles mkt-original: wrote {count} verses for ch 29-31')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
